    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-09-16T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-09-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="594"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d594">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">825.24/211 ²⁄₄</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Chilean Embassy</gloss> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Aide-Mémoire</hi>
                </p>
                <p rend="center">[Translation]</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>—To define the scope of Art. IV, that is, the meaning of the obligation
                        imposed upon Chile to make available defense articles and defense
                        information. If the term “defense articles” includes such strategic products
                        as copper, nitrate and iron, it will be desirable to establish the
                        conditions under which such products would be made available.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>—Art. V would be satisfactory to the Government of Chile if references to
                        consent by the Presidents of the United States and Chile were eliminated,
                        leaving only the solemn promise by both contracting parties not to transfer
                        title to or possession of any defense article or defense information or
                        permit its use by persons not connected with the respective
                        Governments.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>—With reference to Art. VI, we desire to know exactly the obligation which
                        Chile would assume toward any citizen of the United States who has patent
                        rights in any defense article, as well as the scope and meaning which the
                        agreement gives to the obligation to “take any <pb facs="0586" n="576"
                            xml:id="pg_576"/> action or make any payment” to protect the patent
                        rights of American citizens when so requested by the President of the United
                        States.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>—We desire to obtain, as soon as possible, approval on the part of the
                        Government of the United States of some sale formula which will eliminate
                        the idea that a donation is made.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <dateline rendition="#left">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-09-16">September 16,
                            1941</date>.</dateline>
                </closer>
            </div>
